        <?php echo $this->stencil->setHeadline('The Zend Server'); ?>
        <p><strong>Zend Server</strong> refers to a <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('PHP', 'L'); ?> application server product line offered by <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('Zend Technologies', 'C'); ?>, released in early 2009 with production support available for <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('Windows', 'OS'); ?>, <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('Linux', 'OS'); ?>, <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('OS X', 'OS'); ?> and IBM i.</p>
        <p>It is available in five versions. Free, Developer, Small Business, Professional and Enterprise Edition.</p>
        <p>Zend Server is supported on x86 and x86-64 compatible machines with IBM i support in Zend Server 5.</p>
        <p>On Linux, it is supported on <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('Red Hat Enterprise Linux', 'OS'); ?>, <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('CentOS', 'OS'); ?>, <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('Fedora Core', 'OS'); ?>, Oracle Enterprise Linux, <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('Debian', 'OS'); ?> and <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('Ubuntu', 'OS'); ?>. On Windows, Zend Server is supported on <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('Windows Server', 'OS'); ?> 2003/2008, <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('Windows XP', 'WIN'); ?>, <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('Windows Vista', 'WIN'); ?> and <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('Windows 7', 'WIN'); ?>.</p>
        <p>At <strong>Zendcon</strong> 2009 Zend announced the public beta of Zend Server 5.0.</p>
